    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/asynchronous-event-aggregation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "To improve the performance of the tool, we use services with high-throughput APIs when available (e.g. IDSM (Galgonek & Vondr\u00e1\u0161ek, 2021), which can be used to access the Pub Chem database). Since it takes some non-trivial time for the services to respond to a query, this task is suitable for the asynchronous approach, making the tool computationally efficient. Additionally, results containing all metadata related to a compound are cached, making access to all available metadata for a compound result in only a single query. For services with limited access rate (i.e., Pub Chem), we implemented a throttling mechanism \u2013 maximizing performance while mitigating restrictions from the requested webservice.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes asynchronous annotation workflow and throttling for rate-limited services (PubChem), but does NOT describe a dedicated monitoring system that tracks availability, error rates, latency, or generates timestamped JSON health reports. The paper focuses on asynchronous annotation execution and caching/throttling, not service health monitoring.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-04494",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "asynchronous-event-aggregation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Design and implement asynchronous monitoring of multiple external web service endpoints to track availability, error rates, and latency, then aggregate metrics into a timestamped JSON health report.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:49:28.523044+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/asynchronous-event-aggregation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "MSMetaEnhancer is a Python software package for the metadata enrichment of records in mass spectral library files commonly used as reference for chemical identification via mass spectrometry. The package retrieves the respective information by querying several external databases using existing metadata (e.g., SMILES or CAS number), converting different representations or database identifiers. Multiple databases and services are included, currently supporting the chemical identifier resolver (CIR), chemical translation service (CTS) Additionally, instead of querying external databases, computing the identifiers is also supported (e.g. molecular weight from SMILES).",
      "asbval:note": "MSMetaEnhancer does fetch metadata asynchronously from multiple web services (CIR, CTS, IDSM, PubChem, BridgeDb, ChemIDplus), but the paper does NOT describe embedding a Monitor class for tracking service availability. The tool implements throttling and caching but not health monitoring.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-21105-joss-04494",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "asynchronous-event-aggregation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "MSMetaEnhancer \u2014 annotation framework that fetches metadata asynchronously from multiple web services; embeds the Monitor for tracking service availability during annotation runs",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-16T05:49:28.523044+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/asynchronous-event-aggregation/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Since it takes some non-trivial time for the services to respond to a query, this task is suitable for the asynchronous approach, making the tool computationally efficient. ... asyncio.run(app.annotate_spectra(services, jobs))",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms asyncio is used for asynchronous annotation execution, but does NOT describe using asyncio for health-check probes or service monitoring. The asyncio usage is for annotation workflow, not health monitoring.",
